subSection.paragraph:
The discovery of the new subspecies in Sichuan is intriguing and unexpected, owing to the absence of notable geographical isolation from other adjacent regions. The morphological divergence of
A. procris
in Jinchuan and Barkam might be attributed to two factors. The first is that the new subspecies is observed only at relatively low altitudes, as mentioned in the ecological section, where its habitats are constrained by the high mountains. Second, the areas in the upper Dadu River, from Danba, across Jinchuan to W. Barkam, are part of a unique geographical region known as the ‘dry-hot valley’, characterized by high temperatures and low humidity (Y. Hu et al. 2021;
Yang et al. 2022
) ( Fig. 5 ). Consequently, this new subspecies, driven by such ecological opportunity, may have emerged in the dry-hot valley of the upper Dadu River, probably a case of the early stage of budding speciation ( Funk & Omland 2003 ). Subsequently it has extended along the valley to Barkam, but with limited contact with the populations in Heishui and Lixian which belong to the nominate subspecies due to the altitudinal barrier ( Fig. 5 ).
